# Simple English Documentation Rule

Write all documentation and code comments using simple English at B1 level when possible.

## Guidelines:
- Use short, clear sentences
- Choose common words over complex ones
- Avoid unnecessary jargon
- Break complex ideas into smaller parts
- Use active voice when possible

## Exceptions:
- Technical terms that are widely accepted in the field
- Standard programming terminology
- Industry-specific jargon that has no simple equivalent

## Examples:

### Good:
```javascript
// Check if the user is logged in
// This function returns true or false
function isUserLoggedIn() {
    // Code here
}
```

### Avoid:
```javascript
// Ascertain authentication status utilizing comprehensive verification methodology
// This sophisticated function determines user authentication state
function isUserLoggedIn() {
    // Code here
}
```

## Word Choice Guidelines:
- Use "start" instead of "initiate"
- Use "end" instead of "terminate"
- Use "get" instead of "retrieve"
- Use "send" instead of "transmit"
- Use "make" instead of "generate"

Keep technical accuracy while making content accessible to developers with different English skill levels.